ne 1562":"25 juni 1562","1558":"1558","1546":"1546","1566":"1566","1642":"1642","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1564":"1564","1651":"1651","1585":"1585","9 April 1564":"9 april 1564","1549":"1549","1614":"1614","1603":"1603","Ashby St Ledgers, Northamptonshire, England":"Ashby St Ledgers, Northamptonshire, England","Chieveley, Berkshire, England":"Chieveley, Berkshire, England","England":"England","Naseby, Northamptonshire, England":"Naseby, Northamptonshire, England"},"en":{"1546–":"1546–Deceased","1546–1603":"1546–1603","1564–Male":"1564–Deceased","1566–1614":"1566–1614","1546–Male":"1546–Deceased","25 June 1562":"25 June 1562","1558":"1558","1546":"1546","1566":"1566","1642":"1642","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1564":"1564","1651":"1651","1585":"1585","9 April 1564":"9 April 1564","1549":"1549","1614":"1614","1603":"1603","Ashby St Ledgers, Northamptonshire, England":"Ashby St Ledgers, Northamptonshire, England","Chieveley, Berkshire, England":"Chieveley, Berkshire, England","England":"England","Naseby, Northamptonshire, England":"Naseby, Northamptonshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Astyll","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: variant of   Astle   or   Astill  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Astle","meanings":["English: habitational name from a place in Cheshire called Astle, from Old English <i>ēast</i> ‘east’ + <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’. There may also have been some confusion with <i>Asthall</i> and   Astley  . Or occasionally this may be a topographic name denoting residence on an ‘east hill’ (from Middle English <i>ast</i> + <i>hill</i> or <i>hull</i>), i.e. a hill to the east of a settlement.","English: perhaps also a habitational name from Astwell, Northamptonshire, from Old English <i>ēast</i> ‘east’ + <i>wielle</i> ‘spring’.","English: habitational name from Asthall, Oxfordshire, from Old English <i>ēast</i> ‘east’ + <i>halh</i> ‘nook’."]},{"name":"Astill","meanings":["1  English: locative name variant of   Astle  .","2  Norman, English: relationship name from the Middle English personal name  <i>Astill</i>, a contraction of Norman French  <i>Ansketill</i> (Old Scandinavian  <i>Ásketill</i>, with Continental Germanic  <i>Ans-</i> substituted for  <i>As-</i>).  See  Askell  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":3,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705202,"age":12,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705207,"age":39,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705208,"age":41,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705212,"age":74,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705213,"age":96,"year":"1642","toYear":"1651","julianDay":2320789,"title":"The English Civil War","description":"A series of conflicts regarding England's governance during the years 1642 to 1651 is now known as The English Civil War. Charles I summoned supporters to join him against his enemies in Parliament. In October 1642, nearly 10,000 men fought for Charles I and chased Parliament across the River Tamar. Fighting continued for years and was finally ended at the Battle of Worcester on September 3, 1651, with a Parliamentarian victory.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"William Astyll was born in 1546, in England. He married Luce Harbert on 25 June 1562, in Chieveley, Berkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in Ashby St Ledgers, Northamptonshire, England."},"et":{"1546–":"1546–Surnud","1546–1603":"1546–1603","1564–Male":"1564–Surnud","1566–1614":"1566–1614","1546–Male":"1546–Surnud","25 June 1562":"25. juuni 1562","1558":"1558","1546":"1546","1566":"1566","1642":"1642","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1564":"1564","1651":"1651","1585":"1585","9 April 1564":"9. aprill 1564","1549":"1549","1614":"1614","1603":"1603","Ashby St Ledgers, Northamptonshire, England":"Ashby St Ledgers, Northamptonshire, England","Chieveley, Berkshire, England":"Chieveley, Berkshire, England","England":"England","Naseby, Northamptonshire, England":"Naseby, Northamptonshire, England"},"fi":{"1546–":"1546–Kuollut","1546–1603":"1546–1603","1564–Male":"1564–Kuollut","1566–1614":"1566–1614","1546–Male":"1546–Kuollut","25 June 1562":"25. kesäkuuta 1562","1558":"1558","1546":"1546","1566":"1566","1642":"1642","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1564":"1564","1651":"1651","1585":"1585","9 April 1564":"9. huhtikuuta 1564","1549":"1549","1614":"1614","1603":"1603","Ashby St Ledgers, Northamptonshire, England":"Ashby St Ledgers, Northamptonshire, England","Chieveley, Berkshire, England":"Chieveley, Berkshire, England","England":"England","Naseby, Northamptonshire, England":"Naseby, Northamptonshire, England"},"fr":{"1546–":"1546–Décédé","1546–1603":"1546–1603","1564–Male":"1564–Décédé","1566–1614":"1566–1614","1546–Male":"1546–Décédé","25 June 1562":"25 juin 1562","1558":"1558","1546":"1546","1566":"1566","1642":"1642","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1564":"1564","1651":"1651","1585":"1585","9 April 1564":"9 avril 1564","1549":"1549","1614":"1614","1603":"1603","Ashby St Ledgers, North